{"cursor":"4760","size":15,"audio":[],"currentlang":"en","article":"{{Infobox comet\n| name=C/1680 V1 image= caption=The Great Comet of 1680 over Rotterdam\n| discoverer=Gottfried Kirch discovery_date=1680-11-14 designations=Great Comet\n| of 1680, 1680 V1 epoch=1680-Nov-29.0 2335000.5(?) semimajor=444 AU\n| perihelion=0.00622 AU {{cite web\n  |date=1681-03-19 last obs (Encke : 125 day data arc) |title=JPL Small-Body\n  Database Browser: C/1680 V1\n  |url=http://ssd.jpl.nasa.gov/sbdb.cgi?sstr=C/1680+V1 |publisher=Jet Propulsion\n  Laboratory |accessdate=2011-07-26}}\n| aphelion=889 AU eccentricity=0.999986 period=~10,000 yr {{cite web\n  |author=Horizons output |url=http://ssd.jpl.nasa.gov/horizons.cgi?find_body=1-\n  &body_group=sb&sstr=C/1680+V1 |title=Barycentric Osculating Orbital Elements\n  for Comet C/1680 V1 |accessdate=2011-07-26}} (Solution using the Solar System\n  Barycenter and barycentric coordinates. Select Ephemeris Type:Elements and\n  Center:@0)\n| inclination= 60.7Â° last_p=1680-12-18 next_p=unknown\n}} 'C/1680 V1', also called 'the [[Great Comet]] of 1680', 'Kirch's Comet', and\n'Newton's Comet', has the distinction of being the first comet discovered by\ntelescope. It was discovered by Gottfried Kirch on 14 November 1680, New Style,\nand became one of the brightest comets of the 17th century â reputedly visible\neven in daytime â and was noted for its spectacularly long tail.\nPassing 0.42 AUs from Earth on 30 November 1680, it sped\naround an incredibly close perihelion of on 18 December 1680, reaching its peak\nbrightness on 29 December as it rushed outward again. It was last observed on 19\nMarch 1681. the comet was about 253 AU from the\nSun. NASA.\n[http://ssd.jpl.nasa.gov/horizons.cgi?find_body=1&body_group=sb&sstr=C/1680+V1\nJPL HORIZONS ephemeris] more accurate position, no plot.\n\nWhile the Kirch Comet of 1680â1681 was discovered and subsequently named for\nGottfried Kirch, credit must also be given to Eusebio Kino, the Spaniard Jesuit\npriest who charted the cometâs course. During his delayed departure for Mexico,\nKino began his observations of the comet in CÃ¡diz in late 1680. Upon his arrival\nin Mexico City, he published his ExposisiÃ³n [sic] astronÃ³mica de el cometa\n(Mexico City, 1681) in which he presented his findings. Kinoâs ExposisiÃ³n\nastronÃ³mica is among the earliest scientific treatises published by a European\nin the New World. H. E. BOLTON. Kinoâs Historical Memoir of the PimerÃ­a\nAlta. Cleveland, OH (USA): Arthur H. Clark, 1919. Reprint 1949.\n\nAlthough it was undeniably a sungrazing comet, it was probably not part of the\nKreutz family. Aside from its brilliance, it is probably most noted\nfor being used by Isaac Newton to test and verify Kepler's laws.\n","linknr":165,"url":"Great_Comet_of_1680","recorded":1376422892,"links":["/w/index.php?title=Great_Comet_of_1680&action=edit","/w/index.php?title=Great_Comet_of_1680&action=edit","//bits.wikimedia.org/favicon/wikipedia.ico","/w/opensearch_desc.php","//en.wikipedia.org/w/api.php?action=rsd","//creativecommons.org/licenses/by-sa/3.0/","/w/index.php?title=Special:RecentChanges&feed=atom","http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Great_Comet_of_1680","//bits.wikimedia.org/en.wikipedia.org/load.php?debug=false&lang=en&modules=ext.gadget.DRN-wizard%2CReferenceTooltips%2Ccharinsert%2Cteahouse%7Cext.rtlcite%2Cwikihiero%7Cext.uls.nojs%7Cmediawiki.legacy.commonPrint%2Cshared%7Cmw.PopUpMediaTransform%7Cskins.vector&only=styles&skin=vector&*","//bits.wikimedia.org/en.wikipedia.org/load.php?debug=false&lang=en&modules=ext.visualEditor.viewPageTarget.noscript&only=styles&skin=vector&*","//bits.wikimedia.org/en.wikipedia.org/load.php?debug=false&lang=en&modules=site&only=styles&skin=vector&*","//bits.wikimedia.org/en.wikipedia.org/load.php?debug=false&lang=en&modules=startup&only=scripts&skin=vector&*","//bits.wikimedia.org/geoiplookup","//meta.wikimedia.org","#mw-navigation","#p-search","/wiki/File:Verschuier1680.jpg","//upload.wikimedi